  <p>
    The degree measurements of coterminal angles always differ by an integer multiple of <m>360^{\circ}</m> and angles whose degree measurements differ by an integer multiple of <m>360^{\circ}</m> are always coterminal.
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine the quadrant in which the angles in standard position with measurements of <m>21,354^{\circ}</m> and <m>-12,344^{\circ}</m> terminate.  Also, for each of the stated measurements, determine the measurement of the coterminal angle whose measurement is between <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>360^{\circ}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let's begin with <m>21,354^{\circ}</m>. The first thing we need to determine is the number of times 360 divides 21,254.  This will tell us how many complete revolutions are made before the final partial revolution.
        <me>\frac{21,254}{60} \approx 59.039</me>
        This tells us that the angle makes 59 complete revolutions plus a tiny bit more.  Since the rotation is counterclockwise, the angle terminates in Quadrant I.
      </p>
      <p>
        To determine the desired coterminal angle, let's subtract away the 59 complete revolutions.
        <me>21,354^{\circ}-59 \cdot 360^{\circ}=14^{\circ}</me>
        So in standard position, a <m>21,354^{\circ}</m> angle is coterminal with a <m>14^{\circ}</m> angle.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let's move on to <m>-12,344^{\circ}</m>.
        <me>\frac{12,344}{360} \approx 34.29</me>
        So the angle makes 34 complete revolutions and then a little more than a quarter of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the clockwise direction, the angle terminates in Quadrant III.
      </p>
      <p>
        To determine the desired coterminal angle, we need to start at <m>-12,344^{\circ}</m> and add 35 complete revolutions in the counterclockwise direction.
        <me>-12,344^{\circ}+35 \cdot 360^{\circ}=256^{\circ}</me>
        So in standard position, a <m>-12,344^{\circ}</m> angle is coterminal with a <m>256^{\circ}</m> angle.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  <p>
    Let's make note of the fact that when drawn in standard position, <m>\pi\,\text{rad}</m> and <m>180^{\circ}</m> both generate one-half of a complete revolution in the counterclockwise direction.  Because of this, <m>\pi\,\text{rad}=180^{\circ}</m>.  We can use this fact to convert between radian measurement and degree measurement.
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Convert <m>220^{\circ}</m> to its equivalent radian measurement and then convert <m>-\frac{5\pi}{9}\,\text{rad}</m> to its equivalent degree measurement.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Because <m>\pi\,\text{rad}=180^{\circ}</m>, both <m>\frac{\pi\,\text{rad}}{180^{\circ}}</m> and <m>\frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi \text{rad}}</m> are equivalent to the unitless value of one.  Consequently, we can multiply by the fraction with the new unit in the numerator and existent unit in the denominator to produce the desired equivalent measurement.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>220^{\circ}\amp=\frac{220^{\circ}}{1} \cdot \frac{\pi\,\text{rad}}{180^{\circ}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{11\pi}{9}\,\text{rad}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>-\frac{5\pi}{9}\,\text{rad}\amp=-\frac{5\pi}{9}\,\text{rad} \cdot \frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi\,\text{rad}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-100^{\circ}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

      </sidebyside>
    </solution>
  </example>
  <p></p>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      The length of an arc, s, traced along a circle with whose radius is r and cut by an angle with a vertex at the center of the circle with a <emphasisis>radian measurement</emphasisis> of <m>\theta</m> is determined by the equation <m>s=r\theta</m>.  This is illustrated in <xref ref="trigonometry-the-unit-circle-figure-16">Figure</xref>.  When we solve the arc length equation for <m>\theta</m>, we get the following equation, which has a startling implication with regards to the radian unit.
      <me>\theta=\frac{s}{r}</me>
    </p>

     <figure xml:id="trigonometry-the-unit-circle-figure-16">
      <caption>Arc Length: <m>s=r\theta</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          An angle is drawn in quadrant 1 with both sides terminating at a circle whose radius is labeled as r. The angle is labeled as theta and the arc formed along the circle between the two sides of the angle is labeled as s.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                          width=10cm,
                          xmin=-1.5,xmax=1.5,
                          ymin=-1.5,ymax=1.5]
              \addplot [domain=0:360,samples=100,color=blue,line width=0.5pt,dashed] ({cos(x)},{sin(x)});
              \addplot [domain=20:85,samples=100,color=red,line width=1pt,-] ({cos(x)},{sin(x)}) node[pos=0.5,above] {$s$};
              \addplot [domain=20:85,samples=100,color=black,line width=1pt,-] ({0.1*cos(x)},{0.1*sin(x)}) node[pos=0.5,above right] {$\theta$};
              \addplot [domain=0:0.94,line width=1.5pt,-,color=green!40!black] {tan(20)*x} node[pos=0.5,above] {$r$};
              \addplot [domain=0:0.087,line width=1.5pt,-,color=green!40!black] {tan(85)*x};                    
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </sidebyside>
  <p>
    Suppose that you draw an arc of length 7 cm atop a circle that has a radius of 21 cm.  Then the measurement of the central angle is derived as follows.
    <md>
      <mrow>\theta\amp=\frac{s}{r}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=\frac{7\,\text{cm}}{21\,\text{cm}}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{3}</mrow> 
    </md>
    Where's the unit?  There is no unit!  The units of cm divided to one and left nothing (unit-wise) in their wake.  
  </p>
  <p>
    It turns out that the radian unit is something of a sham.  When we say "three radians" what we really mean is "three."  So why do we use the word radian at all?  To contextual the reader to the fact that we are referring to "three" as the measurement of an angle or an amount of rotation.  Because radians are not a real thing, we generally do not write it out - e.g., we write <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> and contextually recognize that we are referencing a "radian measurement."  When making angle measurement references, the omission of a unit always indicates that we should interpret the value as a radian measurement.  For this reason, it is vital that you include a degree symbol when stating a measurement in terms of degrees.
  </p>
  <exercises>
    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each stated value of <m>\theta</m>, determine the quadrant in which the angle terminates and determine the angle with a measurement between <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>360^{\circ}</m> that is coterminal with <m>\theta</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=15,722^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
           We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.
            <me>\frac{15,722}{360} \approx 43.67</me>
            So the angle makes 43 complete revolutions plus a little less than three-quarters of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the counterclockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is positive), the angle terminates in Quadrant III.
            <me>15,722^{\circ}-43 \cdot360^{\circ}=242^{\circ}</me>
            This tells us that a <m>15,722^{\circ}</m> angle is coterminal with a <m>242^{\circ}</m> angle.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=-2,566^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.
            <me>\frac{2,566}{360} \approx 7.13</me>
            So the angle makes 7 complete revolutions plus less than one-quarter of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the clockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is negative), the angle terminates in Quadrant IV.
            <me>-2,566^{\circ}+8 \cdot 360^{\circ}=314^{\circ}</me> 
            This tells us that a <m>-2,566^{\circ}</m> angle is coterminal with a <m>314^{\circ}</m> angle.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\theta=198,170^{\circ}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.
              <me>\frac{198,170}{360} \approx 550.47</me>
              So the angle makes 550 complete revolutions plus a little less than one-half of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the counterclockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is positive), the angle terminates in Quadrant II.
              <me>198,170^{\circ}-550 \cdot 360^{\circ}=170^{\circ}</me>
              This tells us that a <m>-198,170^{\circ}</m> angle is coterminal with a <m>170^{\circ}</m> angle.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=-7,110^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.
            <me>\frac{7,110}{360}=19.75</me>
            So the angle makes 19 complete revolutions plus exactly three-quarters of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the clockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is negative), the angle terminates on the positive <m>y</m>-axis and is coterminal with a <m>90^{\circ}</m> angle
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>
    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each stated value of <m>\theta</m>, determine the quadrant in which the angle terminates and determine the angle with a measurement between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m> that is coterminal with <m>\theta</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=\frac{226\pi}{3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
           We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.  We do this by dividing the value of <m>\theta</m> by <m>2\pi</m> - the number of radians in one complete revolution.
            <me>\frac{\frac{226\pi}{3}}{2\pi} \approx 37.67</me>
            So the angle makes 37 complete revolutions plus a little less than three-quarters of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the counterclockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is positive), the angle terminates in Quadrant III.
            <me>\frac{226\pi}{3}-37 \cdot 2\pi=\frac{4\pi}{3}</me>
            This tells us that an angle of measurement <m>\frac{226\pi}{3}</m> angle is coterminal with an angle of measurement <m>\frac{4\pi}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=3,356</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
           We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.  We do this by dividing the value of <m>\theta</m> by <m>2\pi</m> - the number of radians in one complete revolution.
            <me>\frac{3,356}{2\pi} \approx 534.12</me>
            So the angle makes 534 complete revolutions plus less than one-quarter of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the counterclockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is positive), the angle terminates in Quadrant I.
            <me>3,356-37 \cdot 2\pi \approx 0.779</me>
            This tells us that an angle of measurement <m>3,356</m> angle is (very close to being) coterminal with an angle of measurement <m>0.779</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=-\frac{1781\pi}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
           We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.  We do this by dividing the value of <m>\theta</m> by <m>2\pi</m> - the number of radians in one complete revolution.
            <me>\frac{\frac{1781\pi}{2}}{2\pi} \approx 445.25</me>
            So the angle makes 445 complete revolutions plus exactly one-quarter of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the clockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is negative), the angle terminates on the negative <m>y</m>-axis and is coterminal with <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=-250</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
           We begin by determining how much rotation is left after all of the complete revolutions are made.  We do this by dividing the value of <m>\theta</m> by <m>2\pi</m> - the number of radians in one complete revolution.
            <me>\frac{250}{2\pi} \approx 39.79</me>
            So the angle makes 39 complete revolutions plus a little more than three-quarters of a revolution.  Since the rotation is in the clockwise direction (<m>\theta</m> is negative), the angle terminates in Quadrant I.
            <me>-250+40 \cdot 2\pi \approx 1.327</me>
            This tells us that an angle of measurement <m>-250</m> angle is (very close to being) coterminal with an angle of measurement <m>1.327</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>
    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Convert each degree measurement to its equivalent radian measurement and each radian measurement to its equivalent degree measurement.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>290^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{290^{\circ}}{1} \cdot \frac{\pi}{180^{\circ}}=\frac{29\pi}{18}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>290^{\circ}</m> is equivalent to <m>\frac{29\pi}{18}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>-\frac{101\pi}{4}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>-\frac{101\pi}{4} \cdot \frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}=-4545^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>-\frac{101\pi}{4}</m> is equivalent to <m>-4545^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>240</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let's begin by making note that 240 may look like it should be a degree measurement, but the absence of a degree symbol means that it is in fact a radian measurement.
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{240}{1} \cdot \frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}\amp=\left(\frac{43,200}{\pi}\right)^{\circ}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp \approx 13,750.987^{\circ}</mrow>
            </md>
            <m>240</m> is approximately equivalent to  <m>13,750.987^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{17\pi}{3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{17\pi}{3} \cdot \frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}=1020^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{17\pi}{3}</m> is equivalent to <m>1020^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>-515^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{-515^{\circ}}{1} \cdot \frac{\pi}{180^{\circ}}=-\frac{103\pi}{36}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>-515^{\circ}</m> is equivalent to <m>-\frac{103\pi}{36}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>45</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let's begin by making note that 45 may look like it should be a degree measurement, but the absence of a degree symbol means that it is in fact a radian measurement.
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{45}{1} \cdot \frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}\amp=\left(\frac{8100}{\pi}\right)^{\circ}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp \approx 2,578.310^{\circ}</mrow>
            </md>
            <m>45</m> is approximately equivalent to <m>2,578.310^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>









